The issue is that two people I know and respect have told me they are excited and definitely going. Most people don’t give a fuck about what’s happening behind the scenes with production and scripting. Unless you care about that, all you know is that a new star was film is out and you want to see it. The unforgivable part is that they will still enjoy it, but they will say “it was alright”
And that’s the issue with cinema these days. Box office zombies that really don’t care and don’t have the inclination to be critical. They are happy with standard shitty shit and they eat it up like pigs.
And that’s the real reason that we have ended up here, with a total mess of a trilogy. Disney gets to keep on profiting and churning out film after film while the pigs keep feasting. Real fans are called a small minority of complainers and the story of star was is ruined.

snippet.textDisplay:
I enjoyed The Force Awakens. Sure, they played it safe and there weren't too many surprises, but the characters were interesting, the sets beautiful and there was a sense of wonder and mysticism.

Then came The Last Jedi, and I loved it. Grandiose cinematography, funny dialogue and a good mix between nostalgia and new stuff. It's not what everyone wanted, but it stands on its own as a Star Wars film.

Now we have The Rise Of Skywalker, and boy oh boy. I'm sorry, it must've been hard to ignore the vitriol for TLJ from a sizable portion of the fandom, and finding a good ending to this billion dollar 9-ology sure is tough. But this is just not a good movie.

It feels designed by committee, but the committee is filled with young teenagers who like lightsabers and force lightning. I felt no creative vision, no driving thread, only loosely sewn together ideas that disappointingly culminate in a "this is the most Star Wars, right?" kinda way.

Nothing about it appears bold or innovative, and the moments where it emotionally connected are cheapened by too convenient resolutions.

Easily the weakest Star Wars in this millenium, sorry JJ.
